# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kinetic-energy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] In physics, **acceleration** is a measure of how fast and in what direction an object's speed and direction of motion are changing.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] It is defined as the rate of change of the velocity.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Like velocity, acceleration has a magnitude and a direction, making it a vector quantity.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The SI unit for acceleration is metre per second squared (m⋅s−2, m/s2).
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The **tangential acceleration** of an object is the component of the **acceleration** which is in the same direction as the motion (or tangential velocity) of the object.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] When the velocity of the object does not change direction, this is called **linear acceleration**.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] **Deceleration** or **retardation**, on the other hand, is the component of the acceleration in the opposite (or antiparallel) direction to the tangential velocity.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] **Radial acceleration** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motions) is the component of the acceleration that changes the direction of the object's velocity.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] In Newtonian mechanics, the acceleration of a mass arises from forces acting on it, with its *net* acceleration being a result of the *net* force acting on it.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] By Newton's second law, the magnitude of the *net* acceleration will be proportional to the magnitude of the *net* force acting on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object, while the direction of the *net* acceleration will be the same as the direction of the *net* force.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] An object's average acceleration ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}$ over a period of time is its change in velocity, $\Delta \mathbf {v}$ , divided by the duration of the period, $\Delta t$ .
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Mathematically, ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}={\frac {\Delta \mathbf {v} }{\Delta t}}.$ The average acceleration is the simplest way to measure acceleration, requiring only knowledge of the change in velocity and the change in time.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] In a strict sense, the average acceleration is the only *true* acceleration one is able to directly measure without appealing to an empirical law, meaning that it is the most fundamental form of acceleration measurement.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The average acceleration is most often used to approximate the kinematics of an object by assuming that the velocity changes linearly with time.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Instantaneous acceleration is the limit of the average acceleration over an infinitesimal interval of time.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Acceleration has the dimensions of velocity (L/T) divided by time, i.e.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The SI unit of acceleration is the metre per second squared (m s−2); or "metre per second per second", as the velocity in metres per second changes by the acceleration value, every second.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] An object moving in a circular motion—such as a satellite orbiting the Earth—is accelerating due to the change of direction of motion, although its speed may be constant.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] In this case it is said to be undergoing *centripetal* (directed towards the center) acceleration.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Proper acceleration, the acceleration of a body relative to a free-fall condition, is measured by an instrument called an accelerometer.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Newton's second law is normally applied in an inertial reference frame.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] In a reference frame accelerating with acceleration a (in one dimension), Newton's laws can still be used by introducing an inertial force (fictitious force) $F=-ma$ on a mass m , opposite the acceleration of the frame.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] This accounts for the tendency of the mass to maintain its inertial motion—to stay "as is," at rest or moving at constant velocity—while the frame accelerates.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] One example is that a person in an elevator feels heavier or lighter as the elevator accelerates or decelerates.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] If m is known, measurement of the supporting force on the mass can be used to infer the acceleration; this is the principle of a mechanical accelerometer.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] In general relativity, gravity and inertial acceleration may be locally indistinguishable (see General relativity).
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] As speeds approach the speed of light, relativistic effects become increasingly large.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] When a vehicle starts from a standstill (zero velocity, in an inertial frame of reference) and travels in a straight line at increasing speeds, it is accelerating in the direction of travel.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] If the vehicle turns, an acceleration occurs toward the new direction and changes its motion vector.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The component of acceleration of the vehicle in the direction of its velocity is called a **linear acceleration** or **tangential acceleration**, its effect being the passengers on board experience as a fictitious force pushing them back into or away from their seats.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] When changing direction, the component of the acceleration perpendicular to the velocity is called **radial** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motion), the reaction to which the passengers experience as a centrifugal force (another fictitious force).
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] If the speed of the vehicle decreases, this is an acceleration in the opposite direction of the velocity vector, sometimes called **deceleration** or **retardation**, and passengers experience the reaction to deceleration as an inertial force pushing them forward.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Such deceleration is often achieved by retrorocket burning in spacecraft.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Both acceleration and deceleration are treated the same, as they are both changes in velocity.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Each of these accelerations (tangential, radial, deceleration) is felt by passengers until their relative (differential) velocity is neutralised in reference to the acceleration due to change in speed.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] where **u**n is the unit (inward) normal vector to the particle's trajectory (also called *the principal normal*), and **r** is its instantaneous radius of curvature based upon the osculating circle at time t.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Geometrical analysis of three-dimensional space curves, which explains tangent, (principal) normal and binormal, is described by the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] A frequently cited example of uniform acceleration is that of an object in free fall in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The acceleration of a falling body in the absence of resistances to motion is dependent only on the gravitational field strength g (also called *acceleration due to gravity*).
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] In particular, the motion can be resolved into two orthogonal parts, one of constant velocity and the other according to the above equations.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] As Galileo showed, the net result is parabolic motion, which describes, e.g., the trajectory of a projectile in vacuum near the surface of Earth.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] plane in a point of an arbitrary curve in any higher dimension.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] In uniform circular motion, that is moving with constant *speed* along a circular path, a particle experiences an acceleration resulting from the change of the direction of the velocity vector, while its magnitude remains constant.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The derivative of the location of a point on a curve with respect to time, i.e. its velocity, turns out to be always exactly tangential to the curve, respectively orthogonal to the radius in this point.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Since in uniform motion the velocity in the tangential direction does not change, the acceleration must be in radial direction, pointing to the center of the circle.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] This acceleration constantly changes the direction of the velocity to be tangent in the neighbouring point, thereby rotating the velocity vector along the circle.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] This acceleration and the mass of the particle determine the necessary centripetal force, directed *toward* the centre of the circle, as the net force acting on this particle to keep it in this uniform circular motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The so-called 'centrifugal force', appearing to act outward on the body, is a so-called pseudo force experienced in the frame of reference of the body in circular motion, due to the body's linear momentum, a vector tangent to the circle of motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The tangential component is given by the angular acceleration $\alpha$ , i.e., the rate of change $\alpha ={\dot {\omega }}$ of the angular speed $\omega$ times the radius r .
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The sign of the tangential component of the acceleration is determined by the sign of the angular acceleration ( $\alpha$ ), and the tangent is always directed at right angles to the radius vector.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] In multi-dimensional Cartesian coordinate systems, acceleration is broken up into components that correspond with each dimensional axis of the coordinate system.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] The special theory of relativity describes the behaviour of objects travelling relative to other objects at speeds approaching that of light in vacuum.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Newtonian mechanics is exactly revealed to be an approximation to reality, valid to great accuracy at lower speeds.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] As the relevant speeds increase toward the speed of light, acceleration no longer follows classical equations.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] As speeds approach that of light, the acceleration produced by a given force decreases, becoming infinitesimally small as light speed is approached; an object with mass can approach this speed asymptotically, but never reach it.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Unless the state of motion of an object is known, it is impossible to distinguish whether an observed force is due to gravity or to acceleration—gravity and inertial acceleration have identical effects.
[src:kinetic-energy/acceleration] Albert Einstein called this the equivalence principle, and said that only observers who feel no force at all—including the force of gravity—are justified in concluding that they are not accelerating.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In philosophy, **potentiality and actuality** are a pair of closely connected principles which Aristotle used to analyze motion, causality, ethics, and physiology in his *Physics*, *Metaphysics*, *Nicomachean Ethics*, and *On the Soul*.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In this context, the concept of potentiality generally refers to any "possibility" that a thing can be said to have.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Aristotle did not consider all possibilities the same, and emphasized the importance of those that become real of their own accord when conditions are right and nothing stops them.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In contrast to potentiality, actuality is the motion, change or activity that represents an exercise or fulfillment of a possibility, when a possibility becomes real in the fullest sense.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Potentiality and actuality reflect Aristotle's belief that events in nature are not all natural in a true sense.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] As he saw it, many things happen accidentally, and therefore not according to the natural purposes of things.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] These concepts, in modified forms, remained very important into the Middle Ages, influencing the development of medieval theology in several ways.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In modern times the dichotomy has gradually lost importance, as understandings of nature and deity have changed.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] However the terminology has also been adapted to new uses, as is most obvious in words like *energy* and *dynamic*.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] These were words first used in modern physics by the German scientist and philosopher, Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] More controversially, Aristotle's concept of entelechy retains influence on occasional calls for the use of "entelechy" in biology.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] "Potentiality" and "potency" are translations of the Ancient Greek word *dunamis* (δύναμις).
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] They refer especially to the way the word is used by Aristotle, as a concept contrasting with "actuality".
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] The Latin translation of *dunamis* is *potentia*, which is the root of the English word "potential"; it is also sometimes used in English-language philosophical texts.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In early modern philosophy, English authors like Hobbes and Locke used the English *power* as their translation of Latin *potentia*.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Throughout his works, Aristotle clearly distinguishes things that are stable or persistent, which hold their own strong natural tendency to a specific type of change, from things that appear to occur by chance.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] He treats these as having a different and more real existence.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In terms of Aristotle's theory of four causes, a material's non-accidental potential is the material cause of the things that can come to be from that material, and one part of how we can understand the substance (*ousia*, sometimes translated as "thinghood") of any separate thing.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] When things are most "fully at work" we can see more fully what kind of thing they really are.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Aristotle says the word can be made clear by looking at examples rather than trying to find a definition.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Two examples of *energeiai* in Aristotle's works are pleasure and happiness (eudaimonia).
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Pleasure is an *energeia* of the human body and mind whereas happiness is more simply the *energeia* of a human being a human.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] *Kinesis*, translated as movement, motion, or in some contexts change, is also explained by Aristotle as a particular type of *energeia*.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Sachs therefore proposed a complex neologism of his own, "being-at-work-staying-the-same." Another translation in recent years is "being-at-an-end", which Sachs also used.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Aristotle discusses motion (*kinēsis*) in his *Physics* quite differently from modern science.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Aristotle's definition of motion is closely connected to his actuality-potentiality distinction.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Taken literally, Aristotle defines motion as the actuality (*entelecheia*) of a "potentiality as such".
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] What Aristotle meant however is the subject of several different interpretations.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] A major difficulty comes from the fact that the terms actuality and potentiality, linked in this definition, are normally understood within Aristotle as opposed to each other.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] On the other hand, the "as such" is important and is explained at length by Aristotle, giving examples of "potentiality as such".
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] For example, the motion of building is the *energeia* of the *dunamis* of the building materials *as building materials* as opposed to anything else they might become, and this potential in the unbuilt materials is referred to by Aristotle as "the buildable".
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] So the motion of building is the actualization of "the buildable" and not the actualization of a house as such, nor the actualization of any other possibility which the building materials might have had.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In an influential 1969 paper, Aryeh Kosman divided up previous attempts to explain Aristotle's definition into two types, criticised them, and then gave his own third interpretation.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] While this has not become a consensus, it has been described as having become "orthodox".
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] This and similar more recent publications are the basis of the following summary.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Kosman (1969) and Coope (2009) associate this approach with W.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Sachs (2005) points out that it was also the interpretation of Averroes and Maimonides.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] This interpretation is, to use the words of Ross that "it is the passage to actuality that is *kinesis*" as opposed to any potentiality being an actuality.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Opponents argue that this interpretation requires Ross to assert that Aristotle actually used his own word *entelecheia* wrongly, or inconsistently, only within his definition, making it mean "actualization", which is in conflict with Aristotle's normal use of words.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] According to Sachs (2005) this explanation also can't account for the "as such" in Aristotle's definition.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In a more recent paper on this subject, Kosman associates the view of Aquinas with those of his own critics, David Charles, Jonathan Beere, and Robert Heineman.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] The actuality-potentiality distinction in Aristotle is a key element linked to everything in his physics and metaphysics.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Aristotle describes potentiality and actuality, or potency and action, as one of several distinctions between things that exist or do not exist.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In a sense, a thing that exists potentially does not exist; but, the potential does exist.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] This type of distinction is expressed for several different types of being within Aristotle's categories of being.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Within the works of Aristotle the terms *energeia* and *entelecheia*, often translated as actuality, differ from what is merely actual because they specifically presuppose that all things have a proper kind of activity or work which, if achieved, would be their proper end.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Greek for end in this sense is telos, a component word in *entelecheia* (a work that is the proper end of a thing) and also teleology.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] This is an aspect of Aristotle's theory of four causes and specifically of formal cause (*eidos*, which Aristotle says is *energeia*) and final cause (*telos*).
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In essence this means that Aristotle did not see things as matter in motion only, but also proposed that all things have their own aims or ends.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In other words, for Aristotle (unlike modern science), there is a distinction between things with a natural cause in the strongest sense, and things that truly happen by accident.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] He also distinguishes non-rational from rational potentialities (e.g. the capacity to heat and the capacity to play the flute, respectively), pointing out that the latter require desire or deliberate choice for their actualization.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Because of this style of reasoning, Aristotle is often referred to as having a teleology, and sometimes as having a theory of forms.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] While actuality is linked by Aristotle to his concept of a formal cause, potentiality (or potency) on the other hand, is linked by Aristotle to his concepts of hylomorphic matter and material cause.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Aristotle wrote for example that "matter exists potentially, because it may attain to the form; but when it exists actually, it is then in the form." Teleology is a crucial concept throughout Aristotle's philosophy.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] This means that as well as its central role in his physics and metaphysics, the potentiality-actuality distinction has a significant influence on other areas of Aristotle's thought such as his ethics, biology and psychology.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] The active intellect was a concept Aristotle described that requires an understanding of the actuality-potentiality dichotomy.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Aristotle described this in his *De Anima* (Book 3, Chapter 5, 430a10-25) and covered similar ground in his *Metaphysics* (Book 12, Chapter 7-10).
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] The following is from the *De Anima*, translated by Joe Sachs, with some parenthetic notes about the Greek.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] This has been referred to as one of "the most intensely studied sentences in the history of philosophy." In the *Metaphysics*, Aristotle wrote at more length on a similar subject and is often understood to have equated the active intellect with being the "unmoved mover" and God.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Already in Aristotle's own works, the concept of a distinction between *energeia* and *dunamis* was used in many ways, for example to describe the way striking metaphors work, or human happiness.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Polybius about 150 BC, in his work the *Histories* uses Aristotle's word *energeia* in both an Aristotelian way and also to describe the "clarity and vividness" of things.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Diodorus Siculus in 60-30 BC used the term in a very similar way to Polybius.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] However, Diodorus uses the term to denote qualities unique to individuals.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Using the term in ways that could translated as 'vigor' or 'energy' (in a more modern sense); for society, 'practice' or 'custom'; for a thing, 'operation' or 'working'; like vigor in action.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Already in Plato it is found implicitly the notion of potency and act in his cosmological presentation of becoming (*kinēsis*) and forces (*dunamis*), linked to the ordering intellect, mainly in the description of the Demiurge and the "Receptacle" in his Timaeus.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] It has also been associated to the dyad of Plato's unwritten doctrines, and is involved in the question of being and non-being since from the pre-socratics, as in Heraclitus's mobilism and Parmenides' immobilism.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Plotinus was a late classical pagan philosopher and theologian whose monotheistic re-workings of Plato and Aristotle were influential amongst early Christian theologians.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] This was based largely upon Plotinus' reading of Plato, but also incorporated many Aristotelian concepts, including the unmoved mover as *energeia*.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Other than incorporation of Neoplatonic into Christendom by early Christian theologians such as St.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Augustine, the concepts of *dunamis* and *ergon* (the morphological root of *energeia*) are frequently used in the original Greek New Testament.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] *Dunamis* is used 119 times and *ergon* is used 161 times, usually with the meaning 'power/ability' and 'act/work', respectively.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In Eastern Orthodox Christianity, St Gregory Palamas wrote about the "energies" (actualities; singular *energeia* in Greek, or *actus* in Latin) of God in contrast to God's "essence" (*ousia*).
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] These are two distinct types of existence, with God's energy being the type of existence which people can perceive, while the essence of God is outside of normal existence or non-existence or human understanding, i.e. transcendental, in that it is not caused or created by anything else.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Palamas gave this explanation as part of his defense of the Eastern Orthodox ascetic practice of hesychasm.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Palamism became a standard part of Orthodox dogma after 1351.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In contrast, the position of Western Medieval (or Catholic) Christianity, can be found for example in the philosophy of Thomas Aquinas, who relied on Aristotle's concept of entelechy, when he defined God as *actus purus*, pure act, actuality unmixed with potentiality.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] The existence of a truly distinct essence of God which is not actuality, is not generally accepted in Catholic theology.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] The notion of possibility was greatly analyzed by medieval and modern philosophers.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Aristotle's logical work in this area is considered by some to be an anticipation of modal logic and its treatment of potentiality and time.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Modal logic as a named subject owes much to the writings of the Scholastics, in particular William of Ockham and John Duns Scotus, who reasoned informally in a modal manner, mainly to analyze statements about essence and accident.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Aristotle's metaphysics, his account of nature and causality, was for the most part rejected by the early modern philosophers.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In the works of Thomas Hobbes then, the traditional Aristotelian terms, "*potentia et actus*", are discussed, but he equates them simply to "cause and effect".
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] There was an adaptation of at least one aspect of Aristotle's potentiality and actuality distinction, which has become part of modern physics, although as per Bacon's approach, it is a generalized form of energy, not one connected to specific forms for specific things.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] The definition of energy in modern physics as the product of mass and the square of velocity, was derived by Leibniz, as a correction of Descartes, based upon Galileo's investigation of falling bodies.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] He preferred to refer to it as an *entelecheia* or 'living force' (Latin *vis viva*), but what he defined is today called kinetic energy, and was seen by Leibniz as a modification of Aristotle's *energeia*, and his concept of the potential for movement which is in things.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Instead of each type of physical thing having its own specific tendency to a way of moving or change, as in Aristotle, Leibniz said that force, power, or motion itself could be transferred between things of different types, in such a way that there is a general conservation of this energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In other words, Leibniz's modern version of entelechy or energy obeys its own laws of nature, whereas different types of things do not have their own separate laws of nature.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Leibniz's study of the "entelechy" now known as energy was part of what he called his new science of "dynamics", based on the Greek word *dunamis* and his understanding that he was making a modern version of Aristotle's old dichotomy.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] He also referred to it as the "new science of power and action", (Latin *potentia et effectu* and *potentia et actione*).
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] And it is from him that the modern distinction between statics and dynamics in physics stems.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] The emphasis on *dunamis* in the name of this new science comes from the importance of his discovery of potential energy which is not active, but conserves energy nevertheless.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] A soul, or spirit, according to Leibniz, can be understood as a type of entelechy (or living monad) which has distinct perceptions and memory.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Ideas about potentiality have been related to quantum mechanics, where a wave function in a superposition of potential values (before measurement) has the potential to collapse into one of those values, under the Copenhagen interpretation of quantum mechanics.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In particular, the German physicist Werner Heisenberg called this "a quantitative version of the old concept of 'potentia' in Aristotelian philosophy".
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Terms derived from *dunamis* and *energeia* have become parts of modern scientific vocabulary with a very different meaning from Aristotle's.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] The original meanings are not used by modern philosophers unless they are commenting on classical or medieval philosophy.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In contrast, *entelecheia*, in the form of *entelechy* is a word used much less in technical senses.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] The concept had occupied a central position in the metaphysics of Leibniz, and is closely related to his monad in the sense that each sentient entity contains its own entire universe within it.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Leibniz' use of this concept influenced more than just the development of the vocabulary of modern physics.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Leibniz was also one of the main inspirations for the important movement in philosophy known as German idealism, and within this movement and schools influenced by it entelechy may denote a force propelling one to self-fulfillment.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] In the biological vitalism of Hans Driesch, living things develop by *entelechy*, a common purposive and organising field.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Leading vitalists like Driesch argued that many of the basic problems of biology cannot be solved by a philosophy in which the organism is simply considered a machine.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Vitalism and its concepts like entelechy have since been discarded as without value for scientific practice by the overwhelming majority of professional biologists.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] One example was the American critic and philosopher Kenneth Burke (1897–1993) whose concept of the "terministic screen" illustrates his thought on the subject.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Denis Noble argues that, just as teleological causation is necessary to the social sciences, specific teleological causation in biology, expressing functional purpose, should be restored and that it is already implicit in neo-Darwinism (e.g.
[src:kinetic-energy/actuality-and-potentiality] Teleological analysis proves parsimonious when the level of analysis is appropriate to the complexity of the required 'level' of explanation (e.g. whole body or organ rather than cell mechanism).
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The term high-altitude wind power (HAWP) has been used to refer to AWE systems.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] However, semantically HAWP might also include wind energy conversion systems that are somehow positioned at a large height from the ground or sea surface.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Various mechanisms are proposed for capturing the kinetic energy of winds such as kites, kytoons, aerostats, gliders, gliders with turbines for regenerative soaring, sailplanes with turbines, or other airfoils, including multiple-point building- or terrain-enabled holdings.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Once the mechanical energy is derived from the wind's kinetic energy, then many options are available for using that mechanical energy: direct traction, conversion to electricity aloft or at ground station, conversion to laser or microwave for power beaming to other aircraft or ground receivers.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Winds at higher altitudes become steadier, more persistent, and of higher velocity.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Because power available in wind increases as the cube of velocity (the velocity-cubed law), assuming other parameters remaining the same, doubling a wind's velocity gives 23=8 times the power; tripling the velocity gives 33=27 times the available power.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] With steadier and more predictable winds, high-altitude wind has an advantage over wind near the ground.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Being able to locate HAWP to effective altitudes and using the vertical dimension of airspace for wind farming brings further advantage using high-altitude winds for generating energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] High-altitude wind generators can be adjusted in height and position to maximize energy return, which is impractical with fixed tower-mounted wind generators.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] In each range of altitudes there are altitude-specific concerns being addressed by researchers and developers.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] As altitude increases, tethers increase in length, the temperature of the air changes, and vulnerability to atmospheric lightning changes.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] With increasing altitude, exposure to liabilities increase, costs increase, turbulence exposure changes, likelihood of having the system fly in more than one directional strata of winds increases, and the costs of operation changes.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] HAWP systems that are flown must climb through all intermediate altitudes up to final working altitudes—being at first a low- and then a high- altitude device.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] An atlas of the high-altitude wind power resource has been prepared for all points on Earth.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] A similar atlas of global assessment was developed at Joby Energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] When a scheme's purpose is to propel ships and boats, the objects tether-placed in the wind will tend to have most of the captured energy be in useful tension in the main tether.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The aloft working bodies will be operated to maintain useful tension even while the ship is moving.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] This is the method for powerkiting sports.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] This sector of HAWP is the most installed method.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Folklore suggests that Benjamin Franklin used the traction method of HAWP.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] George Pocock was a pioneer in tugging vehicles by traction.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Solutions in built systems have control mechanisms variously situated.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Some systems are passive, or active, or a mix.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] When a kite steering unit (KSU) is lofted, the KSU may be robotic and self-contained; a KSU may be operated from the ground via radio-control by a live human operator or by smart computer programs.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Some systems have built sensors in the aircraft body that report parameters like position, relative position to other parts.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Kite control units (KCU) have involved more than steering; tether reeling speeds and directions can be adjusted in response to tether tensions and needs of the system during a power-generating phase or return-non-power-generating phase.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The mechanical energy of the device may be converted to heat, sound, electricity, light, tension, pushes, pulls, laser, microwave, chemical changes, or compression of gases.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Traction is a big direct use of the mechanical energy as in tugging cargo ships and kiteboarders.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] There are several methods of getting the mechanical energy from the wind's kinetic energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Lighter-than-air (LTA) moored aerostats are employed as lifters of turbines.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Heavier-than-air (HTA) tethered airfoils are being used as lifters or turbines themselves.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Combinations of LTA and HTA devices in one system are being built and flown to capture HAWP.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Even a family of free-flight airborne devices are represented in the literature that capture the kinetic energy of high-altitude winds (beginning with a description in 1967 by Richard Miller in his book *Without Visible Means of Support*) and a contemporary patent application by Dale C.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Kramer, soaring sailplane competitor, inventor.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] A research on airborne wind turbine technology innovations reveals that the “Kite type AWTs” technique, the most common type, has high scope of growth in the future; it has contributed for about 44% of the total airborne wind energy during 2008–2012.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The kite type AWTs extract energy through wind turbines suspended at high altitudes using kites such as multi-tethered kite, kite and dual purpose circular fan, rotary wing kites etc.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Electricity generation is just one of the options for capturing mechanical energy; however, this option dominates the focus of professionals aiming to supply large amounts of energy to commerce and utilities.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] A long array of secondary options include tugging water turbines, pumping of water, or compressing air or hydrogen.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The position of the electric generator is a distinguishing feature among systems.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Flying the generator aloft is done in a variety of ways.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Keeping the generator at the mooring region is another large design option.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The option in one system of a generator aloft and at the ground station has been used where a small generator operates electronic devices aloft while the ground generator is the big worker to make electricity for significant loads.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The “Carousel” configuration several kites fly at a constant height and higher altitudes, pulling in rotation a generator that moves on a wide circular rail.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] For a large Carousel system, the power obtained can be calculated as of the order of GW, exposing a law that see the power attainable as a function of the diameter raised to the fifth power, while the increment of cost of the generator is linear.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] One method of keeping working HAWP systems aloft is to use buoyant aerostats whether or not the electric generator is lifted or left on the ground.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The aerostats are usually, but not always, shaped to achieve a kiting lifting effect.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Recharging leaked lifting gas receives various solutions.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] In case of productive winds the aerostats are typically blown down by the aerodynamic drag applied on the wide and unavoidable Reynolds surface excluding them de facto from the HAWP category.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Conceptually, two adjacent mountains (natural or terrain-enabled) or artificial buildings or towers (urban or artificial) could have a wind turbine suspended between them by use of cables.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] When HAWP is cabled between two mountain tops across a valley, the HAWP device is not airborne, but borne up by the cable system.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] No such systems are known to be in use, though patents teach these methods.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] When non-cabled bridges are the foundation for holding wind turbines high above the ground, then these are grouped with conventional towered turbines and are outside the intent of HAWP where the tethering an airborne system is foundational.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Lightning, aircraft traffic, emergency procedures, system inspections, visibility marking of system parts and its tethers, electrical safety, runaway-wing procedures, over-powering controls, appropriate mooring, and more form the safety environment for HAWP systems.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] There have been several periods of high interest in HAWP before the contemporary activity.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The first period had a high focus on pulling carriages over the lands and capturing atmospheric electricity and lightning for human use.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The second period was in the 1970s and 1980s when research and investment flourished; a drop in oil price resulted in no significant installations of HAWP.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Return on investment (ROI) has been the key parameter; that ROI remains in focus in the current development activity while in the background is the renewable and sustainable energy movement supporting wind power of any kind; but HAWP must compete on ROI with conventional towered solutions.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] A test center at Lista, Norway provides independent verification of research.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Early centuries of kiting demonstrated that the kite is a rotary engine that rotates its tether part about its mooring point and causes hands and arms to move because of the energy captured from higher winds into the mechanical device.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] The tension in the lofted devices performs the work of lifting and pulling body parts and things.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Airborne wind energy (AWE) for HAWP was birthed thousands of years ago; naming what happened and developing the implied potentials of tethered aircraft for doing special works is what is occurring in AWE HAWP.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] What is "low" for some workers is "high" for others.
[src:kinetic-energy/airborne-wind-energy] Autorotation is the basis of a large sector of AWE technology.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut was born in Paris, France, to Jean-Baptiste and Catherine Petit Clairaut.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] The couple had 20 children, however only a few of them survived childbirth.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] He mastered Euclidean geometry and algebra by nine.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] At ten he studied conic sections and the calculus using *Analyse des Infiniment Petits* (1696) by Guillaume de l'Hôpital.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] At the age of twelve he wrote a memoir on four geometrical curves and under his father's tutelage he made such rapid progress in the subject that in his thirteenth year he read before the Académie française an account of the properties of four curves which he had discovered.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] When only sixteen he finished a treatise on Tortuous Curves, *Recherches sur les courbes a double courbure*, which, on its publication in 1731, procured his admission into the Royal Academy of Sciences, although he was below the legal age as he was only eighteen.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] He gave a path-breaking formulae called the distance formulae which helps to find out the distance between any 2 points on the cartesian or XY plane.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut never married and known for leading an active social life.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society of London on 27 October 1737.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] In his research on the calculus, Clairaut discovered the equality of mixed partial derivatives (Clairaut's theorem).
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] He gave a condition under which the differential equation $M(x,y)\,dx+N(x,y)\,dy=0$ was exact, namely, $M_{y}=N_{x}$ .
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] He showed that a differential equation of the form $y=xy'+f(y')$ , now known as Clairaut's equation, could by solved by substituting $p=y'$ and differentiating both sides.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] He also established the existence of the integrating factor for first-order linear differential equations.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] However, he had been anticipated by Nicolas Fatio de Dullier in 1687, and by Johann Bernoulli in a lesson given to L’Hôpital.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] In 1741, Clairaut published *Éléments de Géométrie*, aimed at beginners.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] For Clairaut, it was imperative for students to make discoveries themselves in a form of active, experiential learning.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] He began by comparing geometric shapes to measurements of land, a familiar topic, and covered lines, shapes, and even some three dimensional objects.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Throughout the book, he copiously related geometry to other branches of mathematics as well as physics and astronomy.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Some of the theories and learning methods outlined in the book are still used by teachers today, in geometry and other topics.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] This textbook was so popular that it went through six editions.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] In the eighteenth century, Carl Friedrich Gauss extended the contributions of Clairaut and Christiaan Huygens in the geometry introducing the notion of Gaussian curvature.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut's *Éléments de Algèbre* (1740) was also well-received in Continental Europe.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Its sixth edition was published in 1801.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] In 1736, together with Pierre Louis Maupertuis, he took part in the expedition to Lapland, which was undertaken for the purpose of estimating a degree of the meridian arc.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] The goal of the excursion was to determine the figure of the Earth and to test whether the Earth was an oblate spheroid, as Sir Isaac Newton had claimed in his book *Principia*, or that it was an oblong, as Giovanni Cassini had thought.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Before the expedition team returned to Paris, Clairaut sent his calculations to the Royal Society of London.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] The writing was later published by the society in the 1736–37 volume of *Philosophical Transactions.* Initially, Clairaut disagreed with Newton's conclusion.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] In the article, he outlines several key problems that effectively disprove Newton's calculations, and provides some solutions to the complications.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] The issues addressed include calculating gravitational attraction, the rotation of an ellipsoid on its axis, and the difference in density of an ellipsoid on its axes.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] This meant not only that the Earth is an ellipsoid, but it is flattened more at the poles and is wider at the center, that is, an oblate spheroid.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] His article in *Philosophical Transactions* created much controversy, as he addressed the problems of Newton's theory, but provided few solutions to how to fix the calculations.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] After his return, he published his treatise *Théorie de la figure de la terre* (1743).
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] In this work he promulgated a result, now known as Clairaut's theorem, which connects the gravity at points on the surface of a rotating ellipsoid with the compression and the centrifugal force at the equator.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] His formula gave the Earth's gravitational field strength as a function of latitude.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Under the assumption that the Earth was composed of concentric ellipsoidal shells of uniform density, Clairaut's theorem could be applied to it, and allowed the eccentricity (or deviation from being a perfect sphere) of the Earth to be calculated from surface measurements of gravity.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] In 1849 George Stokes showed that Clairaut's result was true whatever the interior constitution or density of the Earth, provided the surface was a spheroid of equilibrium of small eccentricity.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] One of the most controversial issues of the 18th century was the problem of three bodies, or how the Earth, Moon, and Sun are attracted to one another.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] With the use of the recently founded Leibnizian calculus, Clairaut was able to solve the problem using four differential equations.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] He was also able to incorporate Newton's inverse-square law and law of attraction into his solution, with minor edits to it.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] However, these equations only offered approximate measurement, and no exact calculations.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Another issue still remained with the three body problem; how the Moon rotates on its apsides.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Even Newton could account for only half of the motion of the apsides.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] In fact, Clairaut had at first deemed the dilemma so inexplicable, that he was on the point of publishing a new hypothesis as to the law of attraction.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] The question of the apsides was a heated debate topic in Europe.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Along with Clairaut, there were two other mathematicians who were racing to provide the first explanation for the three body problem; Leonhard Euler and Jean le Rond d'Alembert.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Euler and d'Alembert were arguing against the use of Newtonian laws to solve the three-body problem.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Euler in particular believed that the inverse square law needed revision to accurately calculate the apsides of the Moon.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Despite the hectic competition to come up with the correct solution, Clairaut obtained an ingenious approximate solution of the problem of the three bodies.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] In 1750 he gained the prize of the St Petersburg Academy for his essay *Théorie de la lune*; the team made up of Clairaut, Jérome Lalande and Nicole Reine Lepaute successfully computed the date of the 1759 return of Halley's comet.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] The *Théorie de la lune* is strictly Newtonian in character.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] This contains the explanation of the motion of the apsis.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] It occurred to him to carry the approximation to the third order, and he thereupon found that the result was in accordance with the observations.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] This was followed in 1754 by some lunar tables, which he computed using a form of the discrete Fourier transform.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] The newfound solution to the problem of three bodies ended up meaning more than proving Newton's laws correct.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] The unravelling of the problem of three bodies also had practical importance.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] It allowed sailors to determine the longitudinal direction of their ships, which was crucial not only in sailing to a location, but finding their way home as well.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] This held economic implications as well, because sailors were able to more easily find destinations of trade based on the longitudinal measures.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] In the same work, Clairaut introduced for the first time the theory of potentials, known by that name since the 1828 essay of George Green.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut subsequently wrote various papers on the orbit of the Moon, and on the motion of comets as affected by the perturbation of the planets, particularly on the path of Halley's comet.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] He also used applied mathematics to study Venus, taking accurate measurements of the planet's size and distance from the Earth.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] This was the first precise reckoning of the planet's size.
[src:kinetic-energy/alexis-clairaut] Clairaut used his own contributions to celestial mechanics and astronomy to assist Émilie du Châtelet in her translation and commentary of Newton's *Principia*.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In theoretical physics and mathematical physics, **analytical mechanics**, or **theoretical mechanics** is a collection of closely related formulations of classical mechanics.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics uses *scalar* properties of motion representing the system as a whole—usually its kinetic energy and potential energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The equations of motion are derived from the scalar quantity by some underlying principle about the scalar's variation.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics was developed by many scientists and mathematicians during the 18th century and onward, after Newtonian mechanics.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Newtonian mechanics considers vector quantities of motion, particularly accelerations, momenta, forces, of the constituents of the system; it can also be called *vectorial mechanics*.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] A scalar is a quantity, whereas a vector is represented by quantity and direction.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The results of these two different approaches are equivalent, but the analytical mechanics approach has many advantages for complex problems.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics takes advantage of a system's *constraints* to solve problems.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The constraints limit the degrees of freedom the system can have, and can be used to reduce the number of coordinates needed to solve for the motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The formalism is well suited to arbitrary choices of coordinates, known in the context as generalized coordinates.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The kinetic and potential energies of the system are expressed using these generalized coordinates or momenta, and the equations of motion can be readily set up, thus analytical mechanics allows numerous mechanical problems to be solved with greater efficiency than fully vectorial methods.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] It does not always work for non-conservative forces or dissipative forces like friction, in which case one may revert to Newtonian mechanics.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Two dominant branches of analytical mechanics are Lagrangian mechanics (using generalized coordinates and corresponding generalized velocities in configuration space) and Hamiltonian mechanics (using coordinates and corresponding momenta in phase space).
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Both formulations are equivalent by a Legendre transformation on the generalized coordinates, velocities and momenta; therefore, both contain the same information for describing the dynamics of a system.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] There are other formulations such as Hamilton–Jacobi theory, Routhian mechanics, and Appell's equation of motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] All equations of motion for particles and fields, in any formalism, can be derived from the widely applicable result called the principle of least action.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] One result is Noether's theorem, a statement which connects conservation laws to their associated symmetries.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics does not introduce new physics and is not more general than Newtonian mechanics.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Rather it is a collection of equivalent formalisms which have broad application.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In fact the same principles and formalisms can be used in relativistic mechanics and general relativity, and with some modifications, quantum mechanics and quantum field theory.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics is used widely, from fundamental physics to applied mathematics, particularly chaos theory.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The methods of analytical mechanics apply to discrete particles, each with a finite number of degrees of freedom.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] They can be modified to describe continuous fields or fluids, which have infinite degrees of freedom.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The definitions and equations have a close analogy with those of mechanics.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The goal of mechanical theory is to solve mechanical problems, such as arise in physics and engineering.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Starting from a physical system—such as a mechanism or a star system—a mathematical model is developed in the form of a differential equation.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The model can be solved numerically or analytically to determine the motion of the system.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Newton's vectorial approach to mechanics describes motion with the help of vector quantities such as force, velocity, acceleration.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] These quantities characterise the motion of a body idealised as a "mass point" or a "particle" understood as a single point to which a mass is attached.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Newton's method has been successfully applied to a wide range of physical problems, including the motion of a particle in Earth's gravitational field and the motion of planets around the Sun.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In this approach, Newton's laws describe the motion by a differential equation and then the problem is reduced to the solving of that equation.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] When a mechanical system contains many particles, however (such as a complex mechanism or a fluid), Newton's approach is difficult to apply.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Using a Newtonian approach is possible, under proper precautions, namely isolating each single particle from the others, and determining all the forces acting on it.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Such analysis is cumbersome even in relatively simple systems.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Newton thought that his third law "action equals reaction" would take care of all complications.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] This is false even for such simple system as rotations of a solid body.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In more complicated systems, the vectorial approach cannot give an adequate description.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The analytical approach simplifies problems by treating mechanical systems as ensembles of particles that interact with each other, rather considering each particle as an isolated unit.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In the vectorial approach, forces must be determined individually for each particle, whereas in the analytical approach it is enough to know one single function which contains implicitly all the forces acting on and in the system.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Such simplification is often done using certain kinematic conditions which are stated *a priori*.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] However, the analytical treatment does not require the knowledge of these forces and takes these kinematic conditions for granted.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Still, deriving the equations of motion of a complicated mechanical system requires a unifying basis from which they follow.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] This is provided by various variational principles: behind each set of equations there is a principle that expresses the meaning of the entire set.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Given a fundamental and universal quantity called *action*, the principle that this action be stationary under small variation of some other mechanical quantity generates the required set of differential equations.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The statement of the principle does not require any special coordinate system, and all results are expressed in generalized coordinates.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] This means that the analytical equations of motion do not change upon a coordinate transformation, an invariance property that is lacking in the vectorial equations of motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] It is not altogether clear what is meant by 'solving' a set of differential equations.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] A problem is regarded as solved when the particles coordinates at time *t* are expressed as simple functions of *t* and of parameters defining the initial positions and velocities.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] If one speaks merely of 'functions', then every mechanical problem is solved as soon as it has been well stated in differential equations, because given the initial conditions and *t* determine the coordinates at *t*.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] This is a fact especially at present with the modern methods of computer modelling which provide arithmetical solutions to mechanical problems to any desired degree of accuracy, the differential equations being replaced by difference equations.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Still, though lacking precise definitions, it is obvious that the two-body problem has a simple solution, whereas the three-body problem has not.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The two-body problem is solved by formulas involving parameters; their values can be changed to study the class of all solutions, that is, the mathematical structure of the problem.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Moreover, an accurate mental or drawn picture can be made for the motion of two bodies, and it can be as real and accurate as the real bodies moving and interacting.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In the three-body problem, parameters can also be assigned specific values; however, the solution at these assigned values or a collection of such solutions does not reveal the mathematical structure of the problem.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] As in many other problems, the mathematical structure can be elucidated only by examining the differential equations themselves.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Analytical mechanics aims at even more: not at understanding the mathematical structure of a single mechanical problem, but that of a class of problems so wide that they encompass most of mechanics.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] It concentrates on systems to which Lagrangian or Hamiltonian equations of motion are applicable and that include a very wide range of problems indeed.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Development of analytical mechanics has two objectives: (i) increase the range of solvable problems by developing standard techniques with a wide range of applicability, and (ii) understand the mathematical structure of mechanics.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In the long run, however, (ii) can help (i) more than a concentration on specific problems for which methods have already been designed.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In Newtonian mechanics, one customarily uses all three Cartesian coordinates, or other 3D coordinate system, to refer to a body's position during its motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In physical systems, however, some structure or other system usually constrains the body's motion from taking certain directions and pathways.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] So a full set of Cartesian coordinates is often unneeded, as the constraints determine the evolving relations among the coordinates, which relations can be modeled by equations corresponding to the constraints.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In the Lagrangian and Hamiltonian formalisms, the constraints are incorporated into the motion's geometry, reducing the number of coordinates to the minimum needed to model the motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] These are known as *generalized coordinates*, denoted *qi* (*i* = 1, 2, 3...).
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Generalized coordinates incorporate constraints on the system.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] There is one generalized coordinate *qi* for each degree of freedom (for convenience labelled by an index *i* = 1, 2...*N*), i.e. each way the system can change its configuration; as curvilinear lengths or angles of rotation.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Generalized coordinates are not the same as curvilinear coordinates.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] D'Alembert's principle states that infinitesimal *virtual work* done by a force across reversible displacements is zero, which is the work done by a force consistent with ideal constraints of the system.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The idea of a constraint is useful – since this limits what the system can do, and can provide steps to solving for the motion of the system.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Vector **r** is explicitly dependent on *t* in cases when the constraints vary with time, not just because of **q**(*t*).
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] For time-independent situations, the constraints are also called **scleronomic**, for time-dependent cases they are called **rheonomic**.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] which are a set of *N* second-order ordinary differential equations, one for each *qi*(*t*).
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] This formulation identifies the actual path followed by the motion as a selection of the path over which the time integral of kinetic energy is least, assuming the total energy to be fixed, and imposing no conditions on the time of transit.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] where $\mathbb {R} ^{N}$ is *N*-dimensional real space (see also set-builder notation).
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The particular solution to the Euler–Lagrange equations is called a *(configuration) path or trajectory*, i.e. one particular **q**(*t*) subject to the required initial conditions.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The configuration space can be defined more generally, and indeed more deeply, in terms of topological manifolds and the tangent bundle.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] which are now a set of 2*N* first-order ordinary differential equations, one for each *qi*(*t*) and *pi*(*t*).
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] which is often considered one of Hamilton's equations of motion additionally to the others.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] that is, the Cartesian product of the configuration space and generalized momentum space.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] A particular solution to Hamilton's equations is called a *phase path*, a particular curve (**q**(*t*),**p**(*t*)) subject to the required initial conditions.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] All dynamical variables can be derived from position **q**, momentum **p**, and time *t*, and written as a function of these: *A* = *A*(**q**, **p**, *t*).
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Following are overlapping properties between the Lagrangian and Hamiltonian functions.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] where the departure *t*1 and arrival *t*2 times are fixed.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The term "path" or "trajectory" refers to the time evolution of the system as a path through configuration space ${\mathcal {C}}$ , in other words **q**(*t*) tracing out a path in ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The path for which action is least is the path taken by the system.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] From this principle, *all* equations of motion in classical mechanics can be derived.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] This approach can be extended to fields rather than a system of particles (see below), and underlies the path integral formulation of quantum mechanics, and is used for calculating geodesic motion in general relativity.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] the above transformations are called *canonical transformations*, each function *Gn* is called a generating function of the "*n*th kind" or "type-*n*".
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The transformation of coordinates and momenta can allow simplification for solving Hamilton's equations for a given problem.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The choice of **Q** and **P** is completely arbitrary, but not every choice leads to a canonical transformation.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] If this does not hold then the transformation is not canonical.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] used to solve the HJE by additive separation of variables for a time-independent Hamiltonian *H*.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The study of the solutions of the Hamilton–Jacobi equations leads naturally to the study of symplectic manifolds and symplectic topology.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] In this formulation, the solutions of the Hamilton–Jacobi equations are the integral curves of Hamiltonian vector fields.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Routhian mechanics is a hybrid formulation of Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics, not often used but especially useful for removing cyclic coordinates.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] If the Lagrangian of a system has *s* cyclic coordinates **q** = *q*1, *q*2, ...
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] and *N* − *s* Lagrangian equations in the non cyclic coordinates **ζ**.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Set up in this way, although the Routhian has the form of the Hamiltonian, it can be thought of a Lagrangian with *N* − *s* degrees of freedom.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The coordinates **q** do not have to be cyclic, the partition between which coordinates enter the Hamiltonian equations and those which enter the Lagrangian equations is arbitrary.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] It is simply convenient to let the Hamiltonian equations remove the cyclic coordinates, leaving the non cyclic coordinates to the Lagrangian equations of motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] as well as generalized forces mentioned above in D'Alembert's principle.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] is the acceleration of the *k* particle, the second time derivative of its position vector.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Each acceleration **a***k* is expressed in terms of the generalized accelerations *αr*, likewise each **r**k are expressed in terms the generalized coordinates *qr*.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Generalized coordinates apply to discrete particles.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] For *N* scalar fields, these Lagrangian field equations are a set of *N* second order partial differential equations in the fields, which in general will be coupled and nonlinear.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] This scalar field formulation can be extended to vector fields, tensor fields, and spinor fields.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Originally developed for classical fields, the above formulation is applicable to all physical fields in classical, quantum, and relativistic situations: such as Newtonian gravity, classical electromagnetism, general relativity, and quantum field theory.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] It is a question of determining the correct Lagrangian density to generate the correct field equation.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] For *N* fields, these Hamiltonian field equations are a set of 2*N* first order partial differential equations, which in general will be coupled and nonlinear.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] Each transformation can be described by an operator (i.e. function acting on the position **r** or momentum **p** variables to change them).
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The following are the cases when the operator does not change **r** or **p**, i.e. symmetries.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] where *R*(**n̂**, θ) is the rotation matrix about an axis defined by the unit vector **n̂** and angle θ.
[src:kinetic-energy/analytical-mechanics] The corresponding momenta to *q* will be conserved.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] There are also several historical forms.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:kinetic-energy/ancient-greek] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] In kinematics, **angular acceleration** (symbol ***α***, alpha) is the time derivative of angular velocity.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] Angular acceleration has physical dimensions of inverse time squared, with the SI unit **radian per second squared** (**rad⋅s−2**).
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] In two dimensions, angular acceleration is a pseudoscalar whose sign is taken to be positive if the angular speed increases counterclockwise or decreases clockwise, and is taken to be negative if the angular speed increases clockwise or decreases counterclockwise.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] In three dimensions, angular acceleration is a pseudovector.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] In two dimensions, the orbital angular acceleration is the rate at which the two-dimensional orbital angular velocity of the particle about the origin changes.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] where r is the distance from the origin and $v_{\perp }$ is the cross-radial component of the instantaneous velocity (i.e. the component perpendicular to the position vector), which by convention is positive for counter-clockwise motion and negative for clockwise motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] In two dimensions, angular acceleration is a number with plus or minus sign indicating orientation, but not pointing in a direction.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] The sign is conventionally taken to be positive if the angular speed increases in the counter-clockwise direction or decreases in the clockwise direction, and the sign is taken negative if the angular speed increases in the clockwise direction or decreases in the counter-clockwise direction.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] Angular acceleration then may be termed a pseudoscalar, a numerical quantity which changes sign under a parity inversion, such as inverting one axis or switching the two axes.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] In three dimensions, the orbital angular acceleration is the rate at which three-dimensional orbital angular velocity vector changes with time.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] where $\mathbf {r}$ is the particle's position vector, r its distance from the origin, and $\mathbf {v}$ its velocity vector.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] Since $\mathbf {r} \times \mathbf {v}$ is just $r^{2}{\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ , the second term may be rewritten as $\textstyle -{\frac {2}{r}}{\frac {dr}{dt}}{\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ .
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] This cannot not happen if the position vector is restricted to a fixed plane, in which case ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ has a fixed direction perpendicular to the plane.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] The angular acceleration vector is more properly called a pseudovector: It has three components which transform under rotations in the same way as the Cartesian coordinates of a point do, but which do not transform like Cartesian coordinates under reflections.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] where $\mathbf {F}$ is the net force on the particle.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] Torque is the rotational analogue of force: it induces change in the rotational state of a system, just as force induces change in the translational state of a system.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] As force on a particle is connected to acceleration by the equation $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a}$ , one may write a similar equation connecting torque on a particle to angular acceleration, though this relation is necessarily more complicated.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] where ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}$ is orbital angular acceleration and ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ is orbital angular velocity.
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] which can be interpreted as a "rotational analogue" to $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a}$ , where the quantity $mr^{2}$ (known as the moment of inertia of the particle) plays the role of the mass m .
[src:kinetic-energy/angular-acceleration] However, unlike $\mathbf {F} =m\mathbf {a}$ , this equation does *not* apply to an arbitrary trajectory, only to a trajectory contained within a spherical shell about the origin.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In physics, the **kinetic energy** of an object is the form of energy that it possesses due to its motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In classical mechanics, the kinetic energy of a non-rotating object of mass *m* traveling at a speed *v* is ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}mv^{2}}$ .
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The kinetic energy of an object is equal to the work, or force (F) in the direction of motion times its displacement (s), needed to accelerate the object from rest to its given speed.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The same amount of work is done by the object when decelerating from its current speed to a state of rest.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The SI unit of energy is the joule, while the English unit of energy is the foot-pound.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In relativistic mechanics, ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}mv^{2}}$ is a good approximation of kinetic energy only when *v* is much less than the speed of light.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The adjective *kinetic* has its roots in the Greek word κίνησις *kinesis*, meaning "motion".
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The dichotomy between kinetic energy and potential energy can be traced back to Aristotle's concepts of actuality and potentiality.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The principle of classical mechanics that *E* ∝ *mv*2 is conserved was developed by Gottfried Leibniz and Johann Bernoulli, who described kinetic energy as the *living force* or *vis viva*.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Willem 's Gravesande of the Netherlands provided experimental evidence of this relationship in 1722.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] By dropping weights from different heights into a block of clay, Gravesande determined that their penetration depth was proportional to the square of their impact speed. Émilie du Châtelet recognized the implications of the experiment and published an explanation.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The terms *kinetic energy* and *work* in their present scientific meanings date back to the mid-19th century.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Early understandings of these ideas can be attributed to Thomas Young, who in his 1802 lecture to the Royal Society, was the first to use the term *energy* to refer to kinetic energy in its modern sense, instead of *vis viva*.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Gaspard-Gustave Coriolis published in 1829 the paper titled *Du Calcul de l'Effet des Machines* outlining the mathematics of kinetic energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] William Thomson, later Lord Kelvin, is given the credit for coining the term "kinetic energy" c.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] William Rankine, who had introduced the term "potential energy" in 1853, and the phrase "actual energy" to complement it, later cites William Thomson and Peter Tait as substituting the word "kinetic" for "actual".
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Energy occurs in many forms, including chemical energy, thermal energy, electromagnetic radiation, gravitational energy, electric energy, elastic energy, nuclear energy, and rest energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] These can be categorized in two main classes: potential energy and kinetic energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Kinetic energy is the movement energy of an object.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Kinetic energy can be transferred between objects and transformed into other kinds of energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Kinetic energy may be best understood by examples that demonstrate how it is transformed to and from other forms of energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] For example, a cyclist transfers chemical energy provided by food to the bicycle and cyclist's store of kinetic energy as they increase their speed.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] On a level surface, this speed can be maintained without further work, except to overcome air resistance and friction.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The chemical energy has been converted into kinetic energy, the energy of motion, but the process is not completely efficient and produces thermal energy within the cyclist.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The kinetic energy in the moving cyclist and the bicycle can be converted to other forms.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] For example, the cyclist could encounter a hill just high enough to coast up, so that the bicycle comes to a complete halt at the top.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The kinetic energy has now largely been converted to gravitational potential energy that can be released by freewheeling down the other side of the hill.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Since the bicycle lost some of its energy to friction, it never regains all of its speed without additional pedaling.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The energy is not destroyed; it has only been converted to another form by friction.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Alternatively, the cyclist could connect a dynamo to one of the wheels and generate some electrical energy on the descent.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The bicycle would be traveling slower at the bottom of the hill than without the generator because some of the energy has been diverted into electrical energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Another possibility would be for the cyclist to apply the brakes, in which case the kinetic energy would be dissipated through friction as heat.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Like any physical quantity that is a function of velocity, the kinetic energy of an object depends on the relationship between the object and the observer's frame of reference.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Thus, the kinetic energy of an object is not invariant.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Spacecraft use chemical energy to launch and gain considerable kinetic energy to reach orbital velocity.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In an entirely circular orbit, this kinetic energy remains constant because there is almost no friction in near-earth space.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] However, it becomes apparent at re-entry when some of the kinetic energy is converted to heat.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Disregarding loss or gain however, the sum of the kinetic and potential energy remains constant.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Kinetic energy can be passed from one object to another.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In the game of billiards, the player imposes kinetic energy on the cue ball by striking it with the cue stick.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] If the cue ball collides with another ball, it slows down dramatically, and the ball it hit accelerates as the kinetic energy is passed on to it.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Collisions in billiards are effectively elastic collisions, in which kinetic energy is preserved.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In inelastic collisions, kinetic energy is dissipated in various forms of energy, such as heat, sound and binding energy (breaking bound structures).
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Flywheels have been developed as a method of energy storage.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] This illustrates that kinetic energy is also stored in rotational motion.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Several mathematical descriptions of kinetic energy exist that describe it in the appropriate physical situation.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] For objects and processes in common human experience, the formula ⁠1/2⁠mv2 given by classical mechanics is suitable.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] However, if the speed of the object is comparable to the speed of light, relativistic effects become significant and the relativistic formula is used.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] If the object is on the atomic or sub-atomic scale, quantum mechanical effects are significant, and a quantum mechanical model must be employed.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Treatments of kinetic energy depend upon the relative velocity of objects compared to the fixed speed of light.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Speeds experienced directly by humans are **non-relativisitic**; higher speeds require the theory of relativity.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In classical mechanics, the kinetic energy of a *point object* (an object so small that its mass can be assumed to exist at one point), or a non-rotating rigid body depends on the mass of the body as well as its speed.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The kinetic energy is equal to half the product of the mass and the square of the speed.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] where m is the mass and v is the speed (magnitude of the velocity) of the body.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In SI units, mass is measured in kilograms, speed in metres per second, and the resulting kinetic energy is in joules.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] When a person throws a ball, the person does work on it to give it speed as it leaves the hand.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The moving ball can then hit something and push it, doing work on what it hits.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Since the kinetic energy increases with the square of the speed, an object doubling its speed has four times as much kinetic energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] For example, a car traveling twice as fast as another requires four times as much distance to stop, assuming a constant braking force.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] As a consequence of this quadrupling, it takes four times the work to double the speed.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The kinetic energy of any entity depends on the reference frame in which it is measured.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] However, the total energy of an isolated system, i.e. one in which energy can neither enter nor leave, does not change over time in the reference frame in which it is measured.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Thus, the chemical energy converted to kinetic energy by a rocket engine is divided differently between the rocket ship and its exhaust stream depending upon the chosen reference frame.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] But the total energy of the system, including kinetic energy, fuel chemical energy, heat, etc., is conserved over time, regardless of the choice of reference frame.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Different observers moving with different reference frames would however disagree on the value of this conserved energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The kinetic energy of such systems depends on the choice of reference frame: the reference frame that gives the minimum value of that energy is the center of momentum frame, i.e. the reference frame in which the total momentum of the system is zero.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] This minimum kinetic energy contributes to the invariant mass of the system as a whole.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] where we have assumed the relationship **p** = *m* **v** and the validity of Newton's second law.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] This equation states that the kinetic energy (*E*k) is equal to the integral of the dot product of the momentum (**p**) of a body and the infinitesimal change of the velocity (**v**) of the body.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] It is assumed that the body starts with no kinetic energy when it is at rest (motionless).
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] (In this equation the moment of inertia must be taken about an axis through the center of mass and the rotation measured by ω must be around that axis; more general equations exist for systems where the object is subject to wobble due to its eccentric shape).
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] A system of bodies may have internal kinetic energy due to the relative motion of the bodies in the system.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] For example, in the Solar System the planets and planetoids are orbiting the Sun.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In a tank of gas, the molecules are moving in all directions.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The kinetic energy of the system is the sum of the kinetic energies of the bodies it contains.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] These all contribute to the body's mass, as provided by the special theory of relativity.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] When discussing movements of a macroscopic body, the kinetic energy referred to is usually that of the macroscopic movement only.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] However, all internal energies of all types contribute to a body's mass, inertia, and total energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In fluid dynamics, the kinetic energy per unit volume at each point in an incompressible fluid flow field is called the dynamic pressure at that point.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] where q is the dynamic pressure, and ρ is the density of the incompressible fluid.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The speed, and thus the kinetic energy of a single object is frame-dependent (relative): it can take any non-negative value, by choosing a suitable inertial frame of reference.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] For example, a bullet passing an observer has kinetic energy in the reference frame of this observer.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The same bullet is stationary to an observer moving with the same velocity as the bullet, and so has zero kinetic energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] By contrast, the total kinetic energy of a system of objects cannot be reduced to zero by a suitable choice of the inertial reference frame, unless all the objects have the same velocity.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In any other case, the total kinetic energy has a non-zero minimum, as no inertial reference frame can be chosen in which all the objects are stationary.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] This minimum kinetic energy contributes to the system's invariant mass, which is independent of the reference frame.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The total kinetic energy of a system depends on the inertial frame of reference: it is the sum of the total kinetic energy in a center of momentum frame and the kinetic energy the total mass would have if it were concentrated in the center of mass.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] This may be simply shown: let $\textstyle \mathbf {V}$ be the relative velocity of the center of mass frame *i* in the frame *k*.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] ${\textstyle \int {\frac {v_{i}^{2}}{2}}dm=E_{i}}$ is the kinetic energy in the center of mass frame, and ${\textstyle \int dm=M}$ is the total mass. ${\textstyle \int \mathbf {v} _{i}dm}$ is the total momentum in the center of mass frame, which is by definition zero.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Thus the kinetic energy of a system is lowest to center of momentum reference frames, i.e., frames of reference in which the center of mass is stationary (either the center of mass frame or any other center of momentum frame).
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In any different frame of reference, there is additional kinetic energy corresponding to the total mass moving at the speed of the center of mass.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The kinetic energy of the system in the center of momentum frame is a quantity that is invariant (all observers see it to be the same).
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Thus the kinetic energy of a tennis ball in flight is the kinetic energy due to its rotation, plus the kinetic energy due to its translation.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] If a body's speed relative to an inertial frame is a significant fraction of the speed of light, it is necessary to use relativistic mechanics to calculate its kinetic energy relative to that frame.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In relativistic mechanics, energy combines with momentum in a way analogous to the combination of time and space into spacetime.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The energy component in the inertial frame can be expressed as: $E=\gamma mc^{2},$ where ${\textstyle \gamma =1/{\sqrt {1-v^{2}/c^{2}}}}$ and m is the object's (rest) mass, v speed, and *c* the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] If the body is at rest in the inertial frame, $v=0$ and $\gamma =1$ , so its rest energy is defined as $E_{\textrm {rest}}=mc^{2}$ .
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Here $p=m\gamma v$ is the relativistic expression for linear momentum, where ${\textstyle \gamma =1/{\sqrt {1-v^{2}/c^{2}}}}$ and m is the object's (rest) mass, v speed, and *c* the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] At low speeds, the square root can be expanded and the rest energy drops out, giving the Newtonian kinetic energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] At a low speed (*v* ≪ *c*), the relativistic kinetic energy is approximated well by the classical kinetic energy.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] So, the total energy $E_{k}$ can be partitioned into the rest mass energy plus the non-relativistic kinetic energy at low speeds.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] When objects move at a speed much slower than light (e.g. in everyday phenomena on Earth), the first two terms of the series predominate.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] For example, for a speed of 10 km/s (22,000 mph) the correction to the non-relativistic kinetic energy is 0.0417 J/kg (on a non-relativistic kinetic energy of 50 MJ/kg) and for a speed of 100 km/s it is 417 J/kg (on a non-relativistic kinetic energy of 5 GJ/kg).
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] This suggests that the formulae for energy and momentum are not special and axiomatic, but concepts emerging from the equivalence of mass and energy and the principles of relativity.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] and $\tau$ is the proper time of the particle, there is also an expression for the kinetic energy of the particle in general relativity.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] Consider the case of a metric that is diagonal and spatially isotropic (*g**tt*, *g**ss*, *g**ss*, *g**ss*).
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] where Φ is the Newtonian gravitational potential.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] This means clocks run slower and measuring rods are shorter near massive bodies.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] In quantum mechanics, observables like kinetic energy are represented as operators.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] For one particle of mass *m*, the kinetic energy operator appears as a term in the Hamiltonian and is defined in terms of the more fundamental momentum operator ${\hat {p}}$ .
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] where $m_{\text{e}}$ is the mass of the electron and $\nabla _{i}^{2}$ is the Laplacian operator acting upon the coordinates of the *i*th electron and the summation runs over all electrons.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] The density functional formalism of quantum mechanics requires knowledge of the electron density *only*, i.e., it formally does not require knowledge of the wavefunction.
[src:kinetic-energy/kinetic-energy] where $T[\rho ]$ is known as the von Weizsäcker kinetic energy functional.
